They are potentially decent arcade races, but the whole has been pulling down a few unnecessary mistakes that have appeared in the series for more than a few years.
So they are not mistakes, but rather manifestations of some incomprehensible laziness of the developers.
Adventure begins very well.
You are brought into the story, whose main hero Jack has certain personal problems and as a solution is offered to participate in an illegal race across America.
You will sit behind the wheel on the west coast of San Francisco and your task is to arrive first in New York City.
The idea brings with it several interesting elements.
The route is divided into ten stages, and then into more than 50 races.
From this it follows that each race goes on a different track and the stages are set in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t have a moment of feeling that the game would still offer the same thing.
Some of the environments are also very nice to see, although the technical level of graphics corresponds to the previous parts of the series.
So it's nothing world-class.
But driving across the desert, autumn landscape or high in snowy mountains works visually very pleasant.
In addition, the races are from time to time stamped with some unusual element.
In the desert, for example, you will get caught in a sandstorm that significantly reduces visibility.
On the other hand, in the mountains, you must be careful not to be filled with a lava.
In addition, individual races are quite well placed behind each other.
There are only a few types, but that’s enough.
So for a while, you are trying to overtake the desired number of opponents (in essence, a classic race), then you are chasing the time (a classic fight with stopwatches) and then waiting for you, for example, a duel with a single opponent.
This will be done from time to time by the police, who will make all your efforts even more difficult.
The new one is passages outside the car.
Rather, it’s just such an interactive animation, when Jack usually runs away from someone and you need to help him by printing the right buttons at the right times.
Nothing complicated.
It is surprising, however, that these passages are much less in the game than you would expect (especially three).
As a result, it is for the benefit of a thing, because this element does not have the chance to become annoying, and in the context of the above-mentioned, it is thus one of the elements that amplify the game.
The driving model goes in the footsteps of previous parts.
This means that in today’s time it’s definitely not who else, but it can’t be said that it would be a bad thing.
If you are looking for a realistic simulation, you will have to look elsewhere.
But the more action-driven racing of the driving model here still suits quite well, even though we could find better in competition.
So then everything is perfectly fine.
However, problems begin to arise after some time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is no longer very good.
We don’t expect this type of game to count complex deformations and collisions, but if you don’t have the slightest idea of how your car will behave in front of virtually any impact on any object, then it’s probably not all right.
Typically, when driving or passing cars in normal operation, you will sometimes only be able to bite each other slightly, but sometimes in almost the same situation your car will end up in wild pirouettes.
