How travel prices have developed since 1989
Until 1989, only five state travel agencies were allowed in Czechoslovakia: Čedok, Sporturist, CKM, Recreation and Autotourist.
At the time, travel agencies sold only tours to the countries of the Socialist bloc, as travel to the west was very limited.
Czech tourists thus traveled on a holiday to the sea to the NDR (German Democratic Republic), to the Soviet Union (Sochi in Crimea near the Black Sea), to Bulgaria, Romania (both to the Black Sea) and to Hungary (Balaton).
The light exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when the possibility to travel to Yugoslavia was also possible, but then the Yugoslav regime leaned towards the West and the trips of Czech tourists to Yugoslavia were then very limited.
The great paradox of the time of socialism was that it was not possible for the citizens of the socialist bloc (i.e. also the Czechoslovaks) to travel individually freely even within socialist countries.
If a citizen of Czechoslovakia wanted to travel individually to Poland or the Soviet Union, he needed a letter of invitation from that country, otherwise the individual journey was not possible.
Travel agencies at that time also offered tours to the West, but it was necessary to stand the front overnight with a sleeping bag or have a good friend in a travel agency.
However, it was not won either.
The so-called foreign exchange promise, which was a condition for traveling to the West, was not granted to “politically unreliable people” who could not travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so it was not possible to raise funds (Western currency) for a trip to the West without a foreign exchange promise.
However, by far the most often Czechs spent their vacation in the Czech Republic, which resulted in a large number of cottages and cottages that Czechs bought and this habit still survives today.
Travelling Czechs has experienced a real revolution since 1989.
While by 1989 holidays in the NDR or Bulgaria were our maximum, last year the Czechs spent 4.5 million holidays abroad in countries around the world.
A huge paradox that we no longer realize today is that it was not possible to travel freely to the most popular Croatia for us at the moment until 1989, as it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the mid-1990s, visa requirements to neighbouring Western European countries were abolished, which started a huge wave of short-term visits, especially in Vienna and Germany.
The Czechoslovaks couldn’t afford trips to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to look there for at least a moment.
For example, in Paris, Czech tours in parks in tents were sleeping, as our incomes did not allow us to pay for a hotel or pension.
A typical feature of the travel of Czechs at this time was the driving of their own food, canned, salami, etc., in order to save themselves.
Another important moment was the introduction of a freely exchangeable Czech crown, which allowed our tourists to finally buy Western currency after many decades of age.
However, our standard of living and average wages increased, which resulted in another important moment around 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, travel agencies have started to prepare tours regularly since 1997 with charter air traffic services, thus making air trips thanks to the possibility to contract quantity discounts compared to the past incredibly reduced.
In the late 1990s, Czechs had visa-free access to virtually all developed countries of the world, except the United States, which continued to make our travel easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of post-revolutionary travel occurred right in 2000, when due to considerable demand it was delivered from the Czech Republic historically the first direct charter flight to exotic, it was to Thailand.
Since this year, direct charters are flying with Czech tourists to warm distant countries every year, this winter will fly directly from the Czech Republic to 12 exotic destinations.
Exotic countries are currently visiting about 100,000 Czechs a year!
Another interesting moment in this period, which symbolizes our post-revolutionary development, came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. cancelled a visa for Czech tourists and our country was definitely among the most advanced countries in the world.
In 2008, Czechs spent more than half of their holidays abroad for the first time in history (50.3%) and spent more than 15 thousand CZK per person on one foreign holiday for the first time in history.
