Peter Englind’s Emotionally Strong New Book Beauty and the Sorrow: An Intimate History of the First World War begins with such a long list of emerging characters as your head turns.
One advice on how to behave at the moment: Take this page carefully and make it a bookmark.
For you will be very familiar with all the people in Mr. England’s novel storytelling, and this list will serve as a navigation - like a beacon - in moments when, like men and women in the story, you will feel confused and lost in different situations.
Mr. Englund is a Swedish historian and journalist.
He is also a new deputy at the Swedish Academy, which awards the Nobel Prize in Literature.
The book we are talking about here is very unusual - the author himself describes it, quite aptly, as \"anti-historic work\" -
It contains several very well-known names, important treaties or famous battles, on the contrary it almost lacks ambassadors, energetic journalists and discussions about tactics and equipment.
It’s not even a book about what happened, it explains the author, as it were, a book about what it was like, “It’s mainly about feelings, impressions, experiences, and moods.”
“Beauty and sorrow” combines 20 more dozen men and women on both sides of the barricade, from students and botanists to climbers, doctors, rescue drivers and officials.
Some of these people will become heroes.
Others become prisoners of war, lose their limbs, go crazy or die.
Their lives pass like flames of candles inflamed in the church - new ones are added to the entanglement of fates, while others are extinguished.
Mr. Englind's book differs from classical historical novels.
It regulates the idea that the First World War was only about the horrific extortions on the Western Front.
“Beauty and sadness,” he also skilfully explores other places where war drama took place: the Alps, the Balkans, the Eastern Front, Mesopotamia, East Africa.
The soldiers in this book solve problems with the fact that bees nests fall on them, have to spend Christmas in the shadow of the pyramids, or they are struggling with the presence of fly tse-tse.
Almost from the beginning it is a very touching reading.
War consumes people's lives as a natural disaster, like Hurricane Katie smelling gunpowder.
When the shooting of the cannons starts to ring in the distance, and you are the woman who is home with your children, will you run or stay?
Who's coming?
Almost no one understands what is going on, even why the whole war has been waged.
“The vacuum resulting from the lack of facts,” Mr. Englund noted, “was filled with guesses, assumptions, hopes, fears, prejudices, conspiracy theories, dreams, nightmares and fairy tales.”
“Beauty and sorrow” follows the stories of individuals such as Florence Farmborough, an English nurse in the Russian army, and Richard Stumpf, a young sailor serving in the German fleet.
Their stories are taken from CVs, letters, and other already published materials.
Descriptions of their lives can sound scary and engaging, but by integrating tiny moments and details, they are absolutely alive and credible.
Many of them are talking about losing and dealing with it.
In the story of the German student, the author says: “Replacements, everywhere substitutes”
Coffee substitute, aluminum imitation, rubber imitation, paper dressings, wooden buttons
He goes further and describes food substitutes in Germany.
The reference is made of ‘mass made of pressed rice cooked in excavated fat (and supplemented by a false bone of wood), tobacco from dried roots and dried potato peels, shoes with wooden soles -
It notes that there were 837 registered meat substitutes in the production of sausages and 511 registered coffee substitutes.
Some stories are about honor and courage.
One American finds inner impulses for wildness and brutality, and says of war: ‘You will finally understand that this is human nature. Not sitting in comfortable chairs with cigarettes and whiskey, evening newspapers or a good book and pretending that your mask represents civilization, and that there is no barbar behind that scraped self inside.’
On the contrary, a British soldier realizes that he is likely to die soon and no one will even notice it, let alone mourn.
“When a person finally reconciles himself with the sacrifice, he would at least expect it to happen before the eyes of a grateful audience,” he writes.
Instead, he feels like a “condemned man who secretly hangs”
Other comments are about the departure of old Europe and the onset of new horrors.
“The conflict has become more and more an economic competition and a competitive struggle,” Mr. Englund writes, “a war between factories.”
He captured what he calls a “new kind of beast of the coming century: a eloquent and ideologically sworn mass murderer in clothes cut to the degree that he does his bloodshed without getting up from the table.”
