Climate change slows down the economy
During the first year of the government, Maria Lópeze Valdez increased unemployment and unreliability in Sinaloa, with foreign investment falling and the economy with them.
The year 2011 will be written into the economic history of Sinaloa. This is the first year of the government of Maria Lópeze Valdez, which is itself called the government of change. This government brought with it great expectations in terms of economic progress, however, due to adverse climatic conditions at the beginning of the year there was no growth and even a decrease in the main indicators of economic development.
Low February temperatures caused millions of losses in agriculture, limited the possibilities of state economic growth, and reduced economic activity by 3.6% in the first semester of this year, as the agricultural sector experienced a historical decline of 31.16%, which disrupted the dynamics of other economic sectors.
According to a report on the damage caused by the Mexican Council for Sustainable Rural Development, the damage was recorded on 582,835 hectares of cultivated land, of which 78,03% were completely destroyed and partial damage was detected on the remaining 21,07%.
The decline in economic activity until November caused a constant increase in unemployment in the state. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Geography, the rate of unemployment in the state experienced increased growth during the first three quarters. From January to March, 55,053 people of the state of Sinaloa were not employed, which represents the unemployment rate of 4.53% of the economically active population. In the second quarter, unemployment increased to 5.28%, and between July and August, average unemployment continued to rise and reached 6.19%, which represents approximately 74,000 unemployed. Therefore, compared to the first quarter, the number of unemployed increased by 18,969 people.
Less liquidity
For unemployment during the year in the state of Sinaloa, there may be more factors. According to Gerard López Cervantes, director of the Faculty of Economic and Social Sciences UAS, an increase in unemployment can be explained indirectly, based on steps taken at the level of public policy.
“We are witnessing rising unemployment, which is related to various factors. These include, among other things, the loss of liquidity on the market due to the reduction of resources due to legislation approved by Congress in connection with the fight against money laundering. For people who illegally seize dollars, it is not easy for them to earn, invest them or use them for something,” he said.
Stop Migration
López Cervantes said there was also a demographic factor involved in the rise in unemployment.
“The number of people who leave for work abroad, to the United States has decreased, both because of difficult entry and then because even if these people go abroad, it is hard for them to get a job. So people remain and demand work from our state, so unemployment is growing,” he said.
Unreliability
The analysis of the labour market in Sinaloa is also deteriorating due to the growing unreliability that prevails in the field of working conditions. According to the National Institute for Statistics and Democracy, 60.38% of the employed people in the state work without making social security benefits.
Other features of the labour market, such as low wages, are added to unemployment and unreliability. In this administrative area, the lowest salaries from all over the country, as stated by the registers of the Mexican Institute of Social Security and the Secretariat of Labour and Social Planning.
The average monthly income of workers in the state of Sinaloa was 5,352 peset, deep below the national average, which is 7,375 peset.
Shortening of foreign direct investment
Along with the decline in economic activity and the rise in unemployment, the most significant decrease in foreign direct investment over the past 10 years was also recorded in 2011. According to the Ministry of Finance, in the period January to June, foreign direct investment amounted to $630,697, which represents a decrease of 87.74% compared to the amount of $5,143,312 for the same period in the previous year.
On the other hand, the Ministry of Economic Development of the Government lists investments of 17,280 million peseses per year. These investments were directed primarily to companies in the field of services.
Debt
In the context of the economic downturn scenario, the government asked the state congress in July to approve a loan of 3 billion peso. This would be intended to invest in infrastructure projects in 18 urban areas in order to revive the economy. The local congress approved a loan of 2,600 million peso. By November, no gains from debt were recorded in any sector of the state economy.
Reactions
According to representatives of the business sector, the first year of the government, Maria Lópeze Valdés, pointed out the lack of government management skills.
Miguel Loredo López, president of the National Chamber of Transformation, said that in 2011 there was a lack of alignment of the will of individual sectors, including the government itself.
“The development of the economy in Sinaloa was very small during this year. We need to work hard to regain the land we lost this year. In 2012 we need to double our efforts, we lack the harmonisation of efforts of all of us, and especially the correct and synchronized functioning of this new government. Let’s hope next year it will be much better,” he said.
Slow economy
Loredo López said events such as frost stopped the state economy at the beginning of the year and limited its development and growth.
“The weak economic movement was caused by a number of events, including frosts. One of the main consequences was the slowing down of the economy, which was not quickly remembered enough, so that it could re-establish a dynamicity that would allow it to achieve an acceptable level of movement of processes, products and services. That’s why at the end of the year we found ourselves deep under the expected forecasts,” he said.
Redefinition of mission
According to Theodore Salazar Uriarte, president of the Employer Confederation of the Mexican Republic in Sinaloa, the state needs to be pushed to more dynamic productive activities.
“In general, we observe that work is being done. We think we need to prepare a long-term plan in which the objectives and economic direction of the state are redefined, because it is important to mobilise all the potential of the material and human resources that Sinaloa has,” he said.
The work that is ahead of us
President Coparmex stressed the importance of establishing a vision of the future that would better manage the government’s efforts.
“In general, I would say that the government has tried to achieve good results in different areas, some progress has been made in the field of economic development, but it is important to create a long-term plan,” he said.
He stated that the current administration has shown progress in the management of public policy.
“There are elements that allow us to say that the government is trying to be friendly. I can say that there is work done here and I believe that the government is aware that there is a lot of work ahead of us,” he said.
