Mexican Institute of Health Insurance launches research into a gene that causes obesity
The Institute of Health Insurance conducts research with the aim of discovering a gene responsible for the obesity of children and adolescents.
The Mexican Institute of Health Insurance (IMSS) announced that it is conducting research to detect a gene that causes obesity in children and young people. Research called “Obesity genetics in children and adolescents” will allow to obtain results related to overweight.
In a report by the Research Medical Unit in Biochemistry from the Specialized Hospital of the National Health Center of the 21st Century, Miguel Cruz López, explained that a multidisciplinary team composed of doctors, nurses, nutritionists and social workers was established.
This team is based on the support of specialists and pupils of postgraduate studies from the National Institute of Public Health (INSP) and the Centre for Research and Advanced Studies (Cinveststav) of the National Polytechnic Institute (IPN).
A wide public with or without permission can participate in the research. People can come to the participating sports centers of the IMSS in Valle de México, where each council will run tests from 8 o'clock.
He stressed that the research began at the Sport Centre Cuauhtémoc (Mexico State) and since October 8 this activity is also carried out in the Sports Centre of Nezhualcóyolt (East of the Mexican State).
As soon as data from 500 to 600 children are obtained, the study will continue at the Sports Center of Independence (south of the Federal District) and eventually at the Morelos Sports Centre (north of the Federal Centre).
He explained that the aim of this research is to identify the ingredients and importance of genetics in terms of the development of obesity, and to track down risk factors on Mexican children and young people, thus preventing the emergence of chronic degenerative diseases.
On the occasion of the International Day of Diabetes, which is celebrated on 14 November, he recalled that the aim is to collect data from three thousand children and young people between six and 14 years of age, with the consent and under the supervision of parents, for the application of specific nutrition questionnaires.
The questionnaire will also ask about physical activity and family history of hereditary diseases in order to avoid risk factors that could cause diseases such as diabetes or renal insufficiency.
He stated that every Saturday, anthropometric measurements (weight, height, waist circumference) are carried out, blood pressure is measured, glucose levels, triglycerides, cholesterol, insulin are determined, and genes are being studied (trying to identify genes involved in the formation of childhood obesity).
Cruz López said this research reflects the health concerns of health care professionals over the alarming increase in child weight.
'Health surveys conducted between 1999 and 2006 showed that in just six years, only boys experienced an increase in obesity by 77% and girls by 47%. A dramatic increase also occurred in overweight,' said an IMSS expert.
He stated that one of the reasons for the search for indicators is the assumption that the population of the country differs from other populations in its genetic history.
He reported that an average Mexican has 65% Indian-American genetic equipment, 30% European and 5% African. This fact is reflected in genes that are responsible for developing diabetes and overweight.
He explained that general obesity genetics is commonly explained as the inability to burn the excess energy we consume (calorie) and stored in the form of fats.
The researcher explained that the direct benefit of participants is that they get an overall assessment of the condition of children, thus finding out whether they show some known overweight or obesity.
He stated that even the presence of wrinkles of dark color (acantosis) on the neck and forearms indicates the likelihood that a given individual will suffer from metabolic problems and prediabetes.
The information is confidential so far, doctors pass it on in writing to their parents and explain to them all the measurements and lifestyle changes they need to make in order to avoid their children’s diseases.
Cruz López explained that there are three main ingredients that cause overweight, obesity, and other chronic diseases: a sedentary way of life that means a lack of daily physical activity, a full-day sitting before television and the use of means of transport instead of walking at short distances.
Overweight also causes a large calorie intake, that is, a greater consumption of sweetened drinks, carbohydrates (tamales, bread, pizza, Hamburgers, etc.) with a high fat and protein content and a genetic burden that is the subject of this research.
There will be no excuses in Asphalt from UNAM.
Rafael Herrera, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry at UNAM, creates modified asphalts with polymers and thus creates a mixture with better functionality, independently of climatic conditions and temperature.
If the pavement had been properly taken care of, almost 200,000 excavations would not have to be repaired after each period of rain in the Valle de México Metropolitan Area, Rafael Herrera Najér, a scientist at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) of the UNAM, who added that if the construction and maintenance of asphalt pavement were adequate, there would have been a significant limitation of the excavations, or could even be completely removed.
In his lecture, The Technological Cause of Embodiment, which he spoke within the International Year of Chemistry, announced that the laboratory under his leadership is developing modified asphalts with polymers, thereby creating a mixture with similar characteristics as asphalt, but at the same time greater mechanical resistance, both at low and high temperatures.
Herrera Najera believes that this kind of modified asphalt could be used in places with an extremely warm climate, for example in some cities in the north of the country. This would improve functionality and reduce the creation of eccentricities.
He explained that asphalt, the most difficult part of oil, is a grouping of hydrocarbons molecules, molecules with a large molecular weight, which are called asphalt, and others with a low molecular weight, which are called Malteses. Together they add asphalt a typical viscoelastic character.
The Viskoelastic character of asphalt consists in the fact that at high temperatures, about 180 degrees, it acts as a liquid, at 120 degrees it has high viscosity and at 50 degrees it is almost in a solid state, while at low temperatures the asphalt tends to break, he added.
This means that the resistance of asphalt in the streets is not uniform, but changes during the day according to meteorological conditions and temperature, a chemical engineering expert pointed out.
A researcher from the Faculty of Chemistry observed that most of the streets in Ciudad de México are covered with flexible tile, made up of six layers of materials, three of which are mixed with asphalt.
Among the top layers there is an asphalt insert, made up of small stones poured in asphalt and then pressed.
