Nord Stream, the new port of Russian gas to Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline connecting directly to Eastern Europe and led by the Baltic Sea bottom began to function.
It must supply gas equal to the equivalent of 30 million households.
Gazprom, a Russian gas giant, wanted to celebrate this event properly.
More than 500 guests, including four heads of state and government, participated last Tuesday in the inauguration of Nord Stream, a new pipeline that will connect Russia and Germany directly under the sea.
Symbolically German Chancellor Angela Merkel, Russian President Dmitry Medvedev, French Prime Minister François Fillon and his Dutch colleague Mark Rutte turned the Russian gas control valve into a Western European network.
With this new pipeline, 27.5 billion additional cubic meters of Russian gas will flow to Western Europe every year by the first 1 224 km pipeline connecting the St. Petersburg region to the Federal Land of Mecklenburg-Pomorany.
The second pipeline, which must be completed at the end of 2012, will allow a total of 55 billion cubic meters of gas, which is the amount equal to the entire French consumption.
And it is already reminded of the possibility of building a third pipeline on the same route.
For Gazprom, the timely completion of this huge building has the nature of victory.
Poland and the Baltic countries protested strongly against the project.
In fact, Nord Stream will allow gas to be delivered directly to Germany without being run by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
At the same time, these two countries are losing some power: the possibility of pushing Russia with threats of closing access to Western European markets becomes more difficult for them.
This was more strongly expressed by Warsaw, when it did not hesitate to compare Nord Stream to the “new German-Soviet Pact”, citing an alliance between Hitler and Stalin during the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that it is politically sensitive.
Western Europe has gained greater assurance of its purchases by supporting this Russian project.
But it is at the cost of weakening Europe's energy, because the project created cracks between Europeans from the East and the West.
Russia barely managed 5 years ago to advance its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and rich Western countries with high gas consumption, whose bearings are approaching their end.
“This pipeline is part of our partnership with Russia, a new artery that unites us organically,” said François Fillon, in a ceremony opening this pipeline and demonstrating at what point large gas contracts are both political and economic.
All this explains the wide smiles of Gazprom leaders present in large numbers in Lubmin, the gas supply point.
The construction of this pipeline is also an important technical act.
The submarine pipe is made of steel with a concrete shell to protect it from anchors of marine vessels.
It lies at the bottom of the sea at an average depth of 200 m.
During its construction, it was necessary to avoid mine fields from World War II.
“For safety reasons, nearly a hundred had to be removed or destroyed,” said Jens Müller, spokesperson for Nord Stream.
The protection of fauna and flora was also to be increased.
The pipe itself is a long metal snake weighing 242 Eiffels, which is not cut off by valves or maintenance stations for all its length.
One control platform was supposed to be built near Sweden, but the project managers rejected it when the Swedes were little willing to see the Russian state company, as it permanently settles off their coast.
“In the event of a failure, we will stop the gas passage in less than 1 minute,” says Jens Müller.
In case of leaks, the gas contained in the pipeline will escape into the air.
But this case is considered unlikely by the builder, since welds were designed to cause leaks once every 100,000 years.
Controlling the state of the pipeline from the outside is carried out by an underwater robot drawn by a ship, while the inside of the pipeline is controlled by a device that circulates inside.
This cigar-shaped device with a diameter of 1 meter is introduced into the inside of the pipe and is printed with gas.
For the entire three days of the 3 m/s journey, the target will provide accurate information on possible deformations of metal parts.
The pipeline has been designed to operate for 50 years without the need for the slightest repair.
Gas circulation is simply ensured by pressure.
The value of this pressure is 200 bar at the start and 100 bar at the finish.
For the implementation of this project, the forces of five companies joined together.
Gazprom, who holds a 51% stake, remains the head of the position.
German companies E.ON and BASF (15.5% each), as well as Dutch company Gasunie and French group GDF Suez (9% each).
These five companies have created a joint venture called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the pipeline.
The company is based in the city of Zoug, Switzerland, where taxation is extremely advantageous.
Gazprom subsequently leased the company for five years with a contract that could be renewed, all of its capacity for gas transport.
“Gazprom will benefit from the total capacity, whatever the amount of gas actually transported,” said Jens Müller.
The financing of pipeline construction was ensured from 30% of shareholders and 70% of bank loans.
The total cost of work should reach €7.4 billion for both pipes.
For GDF Suez, the investment costs increased to 240 million.
But minority shareholders are sure that their costs will be returned to them, since only Gazprom takes the risk.
The pipeline rises from the Baltic Sea in Lubmin on a sandy coast with pine forests.
The 4,5-meter-high valves form the gas outlet gate.
The sensors measure the pressure, temperature and other characteristics of the incoming gas before being transported to the German pipelines.
As of last Tuesday, the terminal receives 1 million cubic meters of Russian gas every hour.
In achieving full capacity, it will be 3 million per hour and 6 million in 2012.
